What does the phrase "living rules" mean?
Enlighten me!

</comment>
<comment date="Mon, 14 Sep 2009 19:23:04 +0000" editdate="Mon, 14 Sep 2009 19:23:04 +0000" postdate="Mon, 14 Sep 2009 19:23:04 +0000" thumbs="1" username="Infomanohio">
"Living rules" refers to the idea of continuously rewriting an original (or older) document to reflect modern ideas and rules.  There are a lot of people who would like to do the same to the United States Constitution.

In other words, the rules for this game are constantly being updated to reflect new ideas and rules that were written for other games (or later for this game) but can be used to "fix" this game.
</comment>
<comment date="Fri, 06 Feb 2015 19:15:14 +0000" editdate="Fri, 06 Feb 2015 19:15:14 +0000" postdate="Fri, 06 Feb 2015 19:15:14 +0000" thumbs="0" username="gamesbook">
[q="Infomanohio"]"Living rules" refers to the idea of continuously rewriting an original (or older) document to reflect modern ideas and rules.[/q]
No, thats not it at all. "Living rules" is a term from the wargaming community.  It means - bearing in mind the complexity of those games - to fix errors and "patch" in new/modified rules to take care of obscure situations that have arisen in play.
</comment>

